        "type": "text",
        "text": "Perfect! ✅ Circuit built and validated. Here's the summary:\n\n### **Wiring Table**\n\n| Arduino Pin | Component | Pin/Role |\n|---|---|---|\n| A0 (14) | Potentiometer | signal (analog input) |\n| 2 | Segment A | via 220Ω resistor |\n| 3 | Segment B | via 220Ω resistor |\n| 4 | Segment C | via 220Ω resistor |\n| 5 | Segment D | via 220Ω resistor |\n| 6 | Segment E | via 220Ω resistor |\n| 7 | Segment F | via 220Ω resistor |\n| 8 | Segment G | via 220Ω resistor |\n| 5V | Potentiometer | VCC |\n| GND | Display + Potentiometer | GND |\n\n### **How It Works**\n\nThe sketch reads the potentiometer (0–1023) and maps it directly to 0–9. For each digit, the appropriate segments light up using a lookup table driven by `if/else` chains (segment patterns for all 10 digits 0–9).\n\n### **Power Budget**\n\n- **Per-pin draw**: Each segment pin drives ~15 mA (LED through 220Ω at 5V). All 7 segments active = ~105 mA peak.\n- **Total board draw**: ~110 mA (within Uno limit of ~200 mA).\n- **Safety**: ✅ All pins and total draw well within safe limits.\n\nThe display will update continuously as you turn the potentiometer knob—smooth counter from 0 to 9!"
